s over $150, then you really can get that look a lot of people love, the classic direct-flash CCD vibe. But did you catch my point? This thing costs over $150. Who's buying that? Honestly, if it wasn't for shooting videos, I would never buy this. I mean, when people see that $150 price tag, they would ask, why would I spend over $150 on something that just flashes like this? Now, the Monochrome version does have a more unique style. Besides shooting regular black-and-white photos, Besides shooting regular black-and-white photos, it also has a built-in special filter, a red filter. You can turn it on to darken blue skies and get high-contrast black-and-white shots like this. Compared to the last gen, the biggest upgrade on the GR4, aside from some design tweaks and small detail changes, is the sensor. It went from 24 MP, to 25.74 MP. As for the lens, the 40mm equivalent 4X version hasn't been updated yet. So if you're buying a GR4 right now, all three of these models are 28mm. That's a bit wide. For some people, framing can be a little tricky. Of course, you can use digital crop to get a tighter field of view, but you'll lose some image quality. One of the most practical things about this lens, One of the most practical things about this lens, after using it, is the macro mode. You can easily use it to shoot everyday stuff, whether it's food or toys. None of that is a huge issue. And since the GR4 upgraded to five-axis, six-stop stabilization, even a 1.5-second handheld shot is actually usable. But don't expect flagship-level stabilization. It just gives you more room for creative shots. As for autofocus, yes, it's improved this generation. It's now using hybrid AF with better face detection. But you'll still notice focus hunting happening pretty often. Of course, you can switch to the GR series' signature snap focus mode, basically, turn it on, the focus is preset for you to shoot. the focus is preset for you to shoot. But it does take a bit of practice to use well.